ed_at": "2020-08-10T20:24:48Z", "closed_at": null, "author_association": "MEMBER", "active_lock_reason": null, "body": "It's easy to make the mistake of writing `cfg(some_feature_name)` when you mean to write `cfg(feature = \"some_feature_name\")`. The compiler will silently ignore it and treat it as false.\r\n\r\nI'd like to suggest a warn-by-default lint for `cfg(some_feature_name)` in the case where the compiler does not know any other meaning for `some_feature_name`, would otherwise ignore it, *and* there's a feature named `some_feature_name`. The warning could also suggest that the user *might* mean `cfg(feature = \"some_feature_name\")`.", "closed_by": null, "reactions": {"url": "https://api.github.com/repos/rust-lang/rust/issues/75375/reactions", "total_count": 2, "+1": 2, "-1": 0, "laugh": 0, "hooray": 0, "confused": 0, "heart": 0, "rocket": 0, "eyes": 0}, "timeline_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/rust-lang/rust/issues/75375/timeline", "performed_via_github_app": null, "state_reason": null}